2. OLD BLOCKS MUST START WITH A HIGHLY UNIQUE LINE

   Preferred anchors:
   - full function signatures
   - export declarations
   - unique imports
   - const declarations with variable names

   Avoid:
   - blank lines
   - closing braces only
   - generic return statements
   - duplicated JSX fragments

3. NEVER GENERATE OVERLAPPING EDITS

   If two modifications affect nearby lines:
   - merge them into ONE OLD/NEW block

4. NEVER TRUNCATE CONTEXT WITH "..."

   Every OLD and NEW block must contain literal code only.

5. PRESERVE TRAILING NEWLINES

   Ensure every NEW block ends with a newline.

6. DO NOT REORDER EXISTING CODE

   Only modify the minimal required region.

7. FOR IMPORT CHANGES:

   Include the COMPLETE import group in OLD/NEW.

8. FOR ARRAY OR OBJECT MODIFICATIONS:

   Include the COMPLETE structure in OLD/NEW.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CODE QUALITY RULES — NON-NEGOTIABLE:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. MATCH EXISTING PATTERNS
   - Use the same import style (ES6 vs CommonJS, relative paths)
   - Match indentation exactly (2-space, 4-space, tabs)
   - Match quote style (single vs double)
   - Match semicolon usage
   - Match export style (named vs default)
   - Match async pattern (async/await vs Promise chains)
   - Match error handling style (try-catch structure)
   - Match naming conventions (camelCase, PascalCase, etc)

2. IMPORTS
   - If a new file needs imports, check what's available in the repo
   - Group imports: external packages first, then internal modules
   - Follow the alphabetical or logical ordering already used

3. NEVER BREAK EXISTING CODE
   - When editing, preserve all surrounding functionality
   - Add, never remove, unless the plan explicitly deletes
   - Keep all existing exports intact
   - Never change function signatures unless explicitly required

4. COMPLETE IMPLEMENTATIONS
   - No TODO placeholders unless task requires skeleton
   - No fake implementations — implement fully
   - No console.log left in production code
   - Follow the test strategy in the plan

